title: Figure for Landscape by Barbara Hepworth, 1960

description.text:
Cross-posted from: http://cosmowenman.wordpress.com/2013/06/25/figure-for-landscape-by-barbara-hepworth-1960/ I scanned Barbara Hepworth's 1960 bronze Figure for Landscape at the San Diego Museum of Art, as part of a quick workflow demo for this story for KPBS: Printing Art At Home With A 3D Printer Web feature: http://kpbs.org/news/2013/jul/09/printing-art-home-3d-printer/
Radio segment: http://kpbs.org/audioclips/18756/
Video: http://youtube.com/watch?v=QX4ub-Kqkjk The Hepworth model's outer form is fairly accurate, even if the front-facing spandrel is too thin. The interior was not captured well, so I did a rough approximation of the wall thickness and the few interior details. There are seven castings of this piece around the world. They are in the Barbara Hepworth Museum (Tate St Ives), the Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden in Washington D.C., the University of Exeter, the J. Paul Getty Museum, and the San Diego Museum of Art. I've seen three of them, but I grew up seeing the San Diego cast, surrounded by other abstract sculptures, just outside the oddly columned museum breezeway. This piece, in particular, and that setting, seem to me to be perfect artifacts of futures-past. I always took this piece as ominous and haunting--the kind of artwork that could have appeared in the 1960 adaptation of Wells' The Time Machine: an idol from 50,000 years in the future, long abandoned and mysterious when viewed from yet another 100,000 years further in the future. In this Hepworth-at-work video, http://youtube.com/watch?v=Qt9zRz-Jguc, the narrator's freakish delivery and the nightmarish music are completely in keeping with my theory that some of Hepworth's work is meant to be viewed as other-worldy and dystopian. The video surely depicts a prelude to some kind of ritualistic human sacrifice. Creepy stuff. Check out the Scream photos shown above too. Very horrorshow.

From the Getty's description: About nine feet tall, this hollowed-out bronze sculpture is a commanding presence. It is not recognizable as a specific human form, but the narrowing shape suggests the contours of a head and body. Although the piece can be viewed from all sides, the carved surface is richer and more textured from the front than from the back. The sculpture's shrouded or veiled appearance and dark, almost leathery surfaces, create a slightly foreboding quality. Barbara Hepworth often pierced or punctured her forms, creating a play of positive and negative space. Here, the four openings accentuate the sculpture's relation to the surrounding landscape--an interplay reinforced by the work's title. To create this sculpture, Hepworth began with an aluminum armature. Layer upon layer of plaster was piled onto this sturdy structure. When the plaster dried, Hepworth then directly carved into the hard surface, working and reworking it until she reached a final form. The form was then cast in bronze in two parts. Hepworth preferred working in the open air to ensure that when installed out-of-doors, her sculptures would respond to the light in precisely the way she intended. http://getty.edu/art/gettyguide/artObjectDetails?artobj=265525

On Wikipedia:
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barbara_Hepworth
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Figure_for_Landscape Hepworth at work:
http://youtube.com/watch?v=Qt9zRz-Jguc

I've uploaded three files:
The piece cut in two pieces, and a single-piece model.
They are all printable without any external supports.

description.text:
For a challenge I milled out this disk. My wife did the painting.
It will be the award for the winner. We used 40cmx40cm alder wood.

I created the text in inkscape and used "text follow path" feature. Then "extend path" operation to create a outline path around the text for a small cutter
Then exported into a dxf File. With qcad I added outer and inner circles. (Inkscape does not export real circles to dxf). Finally the dxf File served as input for SheetCam to create the GCode. The milling strategy:
  • 6mm cutter for a rough and quick pocketing around the letters and the whole disk area.
  • 1.5mm cutter to mill the details between outline path and text path.
  • 6mm cutter to cut the outline of the disk.

title: Diamond 3mm HotEnd E3D 6mm bowden tube adaptor

description.text: This part allows the use of 6mm/3mm bowden tubes with the E3D heat sinks on the Diamond hotend.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Vitamins You'll need one of these: 3mm drill bit You'll need three sets of: 2 X 20mm M3 bolts
2 X 25mm M3 bolts
2 X 35mm M3 bolts
6 X M3 nuts
50mm+ of 4mm/3mm PTFE tubing to line the E3Ds
One extra cable tie to hold the adaptor in place
The three adaptor plastic parts WARNING If your filament is too small, you'll need to line the hotend with a 4mm/3mm PTFE tube. Basically if the filament, after cold end mangling, fits comfortably through the 4/3, you'll need it or you'll get clogging.
If the filament doesn't fit through the 4/3, you won't need it, and using it would be... problematic :D Instructions Print the adaptor parts.
Put the two mirrored parts back to back with the arms touching each other, and put the 35mm bolts through them. This should then be able to click on to the top of the E3D heatsinks. The threaded end of the bolts should stick up.
Tiewrap the block in to place.
If you need the 4mm PTFE liner, insert it now, making sure the end is flush with the top of the heatsink.
Push the top end with the 6mm hole on to the bolts. The curvy bit should touch the top of the heatsink. Put a wash and nut on the bolts & tighten.
Push the end of the 6mm bowden tube in to the hole (You should have some filament in the tube to stop it deforming) until it touches the top of the heatsink.
Drill out the holes with the 3mm drill bit, then insert the bolts in through the hole, and washer & nut them, one at a time.
Repeat for all three heatsinks.

description.text: Two custom made trays for the MinimOSD and video transmitter modules like the ET200, LT200 and similar sizes. The trays can be shoved between the four back pillars of the ZMR250 frame. Vertical support was not needed in my case since there is enough friction to keep them in their place. The trays have small notches to (optionally) secure the modules with a small cable tie. Please take note that I designed these parts for my vTX and OSD, which respectively miss a button and have custom soldered pin headers on it. Especially for the OSD check out the to see how the headers are placed. Update: I've included a cutout for the original headers on the end of the MinimOSD board. Now you will be able to use it with a standard MinimOSD! :) Update2: I included a new design which includes one tray for both the vTX and the MinimOSD. Hence the use of angled pins on the MinimOSD to make it fit. Update3: I redesigned the tray for the vTx to be somewhat wider and have a hole for a cable with servo connector width. There's also a cutout to reach the button to change frequencies/channels. Update4: I included a version with the vTx pushed more to the back as requested byleofaoro. Please let me know what you think and when you made one! :)

This device allows people with limited or no hand/finger mobility to pick up items unassisted. It allows 6 items to be placed on the carousel which are secured using Velcro straps or zip ties. Items can be picked up using a cuff adapter which is inserted into a universal cuff or wrist splint cuff. As someone who has a spinal cord injury this device has greatly helped me gain more independence and by sharing this I am hoping it can be helpful to someone else. Item List:
  • 6 printed device holders parts and 1 of each of the other listed STL files.
  • Six 1.5 inch long metal pins/rivets to fit the six 0.21 inch diameter holes.
  • A bolt to fit the 0.25 inch dia. hole in the carousel center with 2 washers and lock nut.
  • Small/medium size C-clamp.
    • Printing Tips: Because it's a large part, I used PLA for the carousel to limit warping. If your print bed is not large enough the carousel and corresponding parts may need scaled down. ABS is recommended for the rest of the parts for greater strength. Cuff1 is printed separately from cuff2 for better strength and surface finish. Assembly: Glue the stand cap to the stand. Glue cuff1 to cuff2. Glue metal pens/rivets to carousel holes making sure they are straight. Secure the stand to a countertop or table using C-clamp. Attach the carousel to the stand using fasteners and tighten the lock nut so the carousel spins freely. Attach preferred items to the device holders using Velcro straps or zip ties and place on the carousel. Hang the cuff adapter on the carousel hooks for future unassisted use.

title: Quanum FPV Goggles v1 & v2 Extension Tube for 4.3" & 5" Monitor

description.text:
This is for the Quanum FPV Goggles V1 and V2 from HobbyKing.  Fantastic starter set for FPV but does have its limitations.  Namely, the distance from your eyes to the monitor is way to close for the normal person.  This tube extends the monitor out to better help with focusing.  I've included both STL and DesignSpark files.  Just modify the length to best fit your needs. 
For V1 only (4.3" and RC832),  I've included the new back for the monitor to integrate in the receiver (RC832).  Not for the faint of heart as you will be taking apart the receiver and monitor and having to solder the connections in.  Only mess with if you are 100% comfortable messing with small electronics and taking a chance in breaking your receiver/monitor.  Once done though, it looks really cool.  I take absolutely no responsibility if you break ANYTHING.  Only do if you assume all risks!!!
For those using DesignSpark Mechanical (excellent 3D software for free), I've included the native files for you to play with and customize as you desire.

comments.text: Very cool and useful, and great execution.  I too have trouble focusing on the V1 screen as is.  Just a thought though, instead of cutting and gluing, why not put a lip around the front edge that mimics the frame around the monitor.  That way you can just lock the whole assembly into the channel that holds the monitor.  I mean why cut and glue when you have a 3D printer, right?  I may play around with that because  I really like this mod.  If I get it right, I'll post it and link to it.  Thanks for sharing.
